  <!-- ABOUT / PROJECT DESCRIPTION -->
  <section id="about">
    <div class="section-label">// 01 — Project Description</div>
    <h2>What This Project Does</h2>
 
    <div class="full-desc">
      <p>
        This project simulates the real-time control systems found inside a modern fighter jet — 
        specifically inspired by the avionics and weapon management systems used in programs like 
        Northrop Grumman's aerospace work in Orlando, Florida. It runs on an ESP32 microcontroller 
        using FreeRTOS, the same type of real-time operating system used in safety-critical embedded 
        systems across aerospace and defense.
      </p>
      <p>
        The system has two weapon controls: a <strong style="color:#fff;">missile button</strong> that 
        fires a single weapon (one LED flash), and a <strong style="color:#fff;">machine gun button</strong> 
        that simulates a cannon burst (12 rapid LED flashes). A <strong style="color:#fff;">potentiometer 
        acts as an altimeter</strong> — turn it below 25% and a red LED activates alongside repeated 
        altitude warnings in the serial monitor, just like a real aircraft's ground proximity warning system.
      </p>
      <p>
        Under the hood, each feature runs as its own FreeRTOS task with a defined priority and deadline. 
        The weapon response tasks are <strong style="color: #ff4a00;">Hard real-time</strong> — a missed 
        deadline would mean a failed weapon system. The altitude monitor is 
        <strong style="color: #00ff88;">Soft real-time</strong> — a slight delay is annoying but not 
        catastrophic. This mirrors how real aerospace engineers classify system requirements.
      </p>
    </div>
 
    <div class="description-grid">
      <div class="desc-card">
        <h3>🎯 Missile Fire</h3>
        <p>Press the green button and the weapon LED lights for 300 ms — one missile away. 
           The system uses a binary semaphore so the button task and LED task never conflict.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="desc-card red">
        <h3>🔫 Machine Gun Burst</h3>
        <p>Press the yellow button to trigger 12 rapid LED flashes simulating cannon rounds. 
           Execution time varies with burst length — a real variable-time FreeRTOS task.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="desc-card green">
        <h3>⚠️ Altitude Warning</h3>
        <p>Turn the potentiometer low and the red LED activates. The serial monitor floods 
           with ALTITUDE warnings — just like a GPWS in a real cockpit.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="desc-card">
        <h3>🔧 Built With FreeRTOS</h3>
        <p>Four concurrent tasks plus a hardware ISR run simultaneously on the ESP32, 
           each with defined priorities so critical systems always preempt lower-priority ones.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
 
